Love and especially self-love is one of the things I'm struggling with at the moment. When Adriene said "We're always looking for someone else to fill that love cup, but really we know that it starts with us loving ourselves and being able to advocate for what we need", it really resonated with me. One of the reasons I'm unhappy is that I don't necessarily ask for what I need, fearing that other people might reject me or see me as a burden, as someone who demands too much. I am trying to give myself the permission to ask, but it is hard stopping the feeling of anxiety that I will be Too Much. More work on loving myself ahead of me. Thank you for being there for me, Adriene. <3

Returning to MOVE after taking time off to grieve a major loss. What a profound thing, to stop at RELEASE and return with LOVE. Loss comes with regret (even if you did nothing wrong, you always wish you could have done more) and isolation (no one is walking this exact path, had this exact relationship), so the invitation to move more intentionally towards the rekindling of self-love, self-compassion and worthiness was so needed today. Thank you to Adriene and all the other kind souls in this sangha, walking their own paths at their own pace, but still moving, beyond loss and on to love, completing the circle.

I‚Äôve gotten a day behind on this journey, but there‚Äôs a beautiful synchronicity in the themes that matches what I‚Äôm going through in my own life. We have made the difficult decision to say bye to my sweet pup of 16 years tomorrow (my family got her when I was in the 7th grade!). Because of that, this journey has meant something entirely different for me than when I started. This past week, I‚Äôve shown up to the mat with a broken heart, often starting the practice in tears. And although I always think I‚Äôll cry through the entire practice, inevitably I feel a bit better and a tiny bit healed by the end. Like a warm blanket or a comforting friend, this yoga journey accepts me exactly as I am and has given me the space to feel hard things. Much like my dog has always given me. So I dedicate the rest of my journey and especially todays practice in honor of my dog, Bandit, who is the epitome of love. ‚ù§Ô∏è

The love I am, the love for life, the love for myself, the love my body has for me. I also learn to love myself more with my mind. It‚Äôs so great to show up for yourself on the mat every single day.
